## What happened

relevant code (in main):

```
  List<Map> expectedList = [
    {"name": "updated name", "id": 1, "value": 9876, "num": 456.789},
    {"name": "another name", "id": 2, "value": 12345678, "num": 3.1416}
  ];
  print(expectedList);

```

This happens on build (full restart) for iOS in the iPhone X simulator.  Does not happen when building (full restart) on an android phone plugged in.  

Simpler examples such as:

```
  List<String> l = ["hello", "bye"];
  print(l);
```
and
```
  Map m = {"name": "updated name", "id": 1, "value": 9876, "num": 456.789};
  print(m);
```
work as expected

comment_data.body:
I saw this output from the iOS simulator. It is not valid json; there are no string delimiters, and there is no indication it is a list.
```
{name: updated name, id: 1, value: 9876, num: 456.789}, {name: another name, id: 2, value: 12345678, num: 3.1416}
```

cc @cbracken

Based on `Unable to parse response from Flutter daemon`,
/cc @devoncarew @danrubel who're experts on the daemon and might have some thoughts on what's going on (or at least point to the relevant bit of the code).

Yes, this is an artifact of how we're passing stdout and stderr from the app to the IDE. This will only hit in rare cases. We should likely harden this a bit - so we don't throw parse errors - and look into a better way of encoding the stdout so these types of issues aren't possible.
